    "content": "A group of traditional elders from the Bari region in Puntland has released a public statement regarding ongoing grievances from local traders about conditions at Bosaso Port. The elders, representing key clans in the area, expressed concern over what they described as excessive taxation and lack of transparency in port operations.\n\nThe statement follows months of mounting discontent among business owners who rely on the port for imports and exports. Traders have reportedly faced steep fees and unclear billing practices, which they say undermine their ability to compete. The elders urged Puntland authorities to launch an investigation into port management and to implement reforms that protect local commerce.\n\nBosaso Port is a critical economic hub for Puntland and the wider Somali region, handling a significant share of the country’s maritime trade. For the Somali diaspora, many of whom invest in or send goods through this port, uncertainty around port governance can disrupt supply chains and raise costs for families and businesses abroad.\n\nThe elders’ intervention underscores the role of traditional institutions in mediating economic disputes in the absence of strong state oversight. They called for dialogue between the government, port authorities, and the business community to reach a sustainable solution.\n\nAs of now, Puntland officials have not issued a formal response. The port continues to operate amid the controversy, but traders warn that without changes, they may shift to alternative routes.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/isimada-gobolka-bari-oo-bayaan-kasoo-saaray-xaaladda-dekedda-boosaaso-iyo-saameynta-dhaqaale/423784/",
